[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] The **`MediaStream`** interface of the Media Capture and Streams API represents a stream of media content.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] A stream consists of several **tracks**, such as video or audio tracks.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Each track is specified as an instance of `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] You can obtain a `MediaStream` object either by using the constructor or by calling functions such as `MediaDevices.getUserMedia()`, `MediaDevices.getDisplayMedia()`, or `HTMLCanvasElement.captureStream()` and `HTMLMediaElement.captureStream()`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Creates and returns a new `MediaStream` object.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] You can create an empty stream, a stream which is based upon an existing stream, or a stream that contains a specified list of tracks (specified as an array of `MediaStreamTrack` objects).
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] A Boolean value that returns `true` if the `MediaStream` is active, or `false` otherwise.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] A string containing a 36-character universally unique identifier (UUID) for the object.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Stores a copy of the `MediaStreamTrack` given as argument.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] If the track has already been added to the `MediaStream` object, nothing happens.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Returns a clone of the `MediaStream` object.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] The clone will, however, have a unique value for `id`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Returns a list of the `MediaStreamTrack` objects stored in the `MediaStream` object that have their `kind` attribute set to `audio`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] The order is not defined, and may not only vary from one browser to another, but also from one call to another.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Returns the track whose ID corresponds to the one given in parameters, `trackId`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] If no parameter is given, or if no track with that ID does exist, it returns `null`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] If several tracks have the same ID, it returns the first one.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Returns a list of all `MediaStreamTrack` objects stored in the `MediaStream` object, regardless of the value of the `kind` attribute.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Returns a list of the `MediaStreamTrack` objects stored in the `MediaStream` object that have their `kind` attribute set to `"video"`.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Removes the `MediaStreamTrack` given as argument.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] If the track is not part of the `MediaStream` object, nothing happens.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Fired when a new `MediaStreamTrack` object is added.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Fired when a `MediaStreamTrack` object has been removed.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Fired when the MediaStream is activated.
[src:webrtc/api-mediastream] Fired when the MediaStream is inactivated.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] WebRTC consists of several interrelated APIs and protocols which work together to achieve this.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The documentation you'll find here will help you understand the fundamentals of WebRTC, how to set up and use both data and media connections, and more.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Connections between peers can be made without requiring any special drivers or plug-ins, and can often be made without any intermediary servers.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Connections between two peers are represented by the `RTCPeerConnection` interface.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Once a connection has been established and opened using `RTCPeerConnection`, media streams (`MediaStream`s) and/or data channels (`RTCDataChannel`s) can be added to the connection.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Media streams can consist of any number of tracks of media information; tracks, which are represented by objects based on the `MediaStreamTrack` interface, may contain one of a number of types of media data, including audio, video, and text (such as subtitles or even chapter names).
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Most streams consist of at least one audio track and likely also a video track, and can be used to send and receive both live media or stored media information (such as a streamed movie).
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] You can also use the connection between two peers to exchange arbitrary binary data using the `RTCDataChannel` interface.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] This can be used for back-channel information, metadata exchange, game status packets, file transfers, or even as a primary channel for data transfer.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] WebRTC is in general well supported in modern browsers, but some incompatibilities remain.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The adapter.js library is a shim to insulate apps from these incompatibilities.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Because WebRTC provides interfaces that work together to accomplish a variety of tasks, we have divided up the reference by category.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Please see the sidebar for an alphabetical list.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] These interfaces, dictionaries, and types are used to set up, open, and manage WebRTC connections.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Included are interfaces representing peer media connections, data channels, and interfaces used when exchanging information on the capabilities of each peer in order to select the best possible configuration for a two-way media connection.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Represents a WebRTC connection between the local computer and a remote peer.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] It is used to handle efficient streaming of data between the two peers.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Represents a bi-directional data channel between two peers of a connection.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Represents events that occur while attaching a `RTCDataChannel` to a `RTCPeerConnection`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The only event sent with this interface is `datachannel`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Each `RTCSessionDescription` consists of a description `type` indicating which part of the offer/answer negotiation process it describes and of the SDP descriptor of the session.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Provides information detailing statistics for a connection or for an individual track on the connection; the report can be obtained by calling `RTCPeerConnection.getStats()`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Represents a candidate Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE) server for establishing an `RTCPeerConnection`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Represents information about an ICE transport.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Represents events that occur in relation to ICE candidates with the target, usually an `RTCPeerConnection`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Only one event is of this type: `icecandidate`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Manages the encoding and transmission of data for a `MediaStreamTrack` on an `RTCPeerConnection`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Manages the reception and decoding of data for a `MediaStreamTrack` on an `RTCPeerConnection`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The interface used to represent a `track` event, which indicates that an `RTCRtpReceiver` object was added to the `RTCPeerConnection` object, indicating that a new incoming `MediaStreamTrack` was created and added to the `RTCPeerConnection`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Provides information which describes a Stream Control Transmission Protocol (**SCTP**) transport and also provides a way to access the underlying Datagram Transport Layer Security (**DTLS**) transport over which SCTP packets for all of an `RTCPeerConnection`'s data channels are sent and received.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The amount of data currently buffered by the data channel—as indicated by its `bufferedAmount` property—has decreased to be at or below the channel's minimum buffered data size, as specified by `bufferedAmountLowThreshold`.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The data channel has completed the closing process and is now in the `closed` state.
[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] Its underlying data transport is completely closed at this point.
