[src:webrtc/api-webrtc-api] The API is intentionally similar to the WebSocket API, so that the same programming model can be used for each.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The **`getUserMedia()`** method of the `MediaDevices` interface prompts the user for permission to use a media input which produces a `MediaStream` with tracks containing the requested types of media.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `MediaStream` object.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If the user denies permission, or matching media is not available, then the promise is rejected with `NotAllowedError` or `NotFoundError` `DOMException` respectively.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] An object specifying the types of media to request, along with any requirements for each type.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The `constraints` parameter is an object with two members: `video` and `audio`, describing the media types requested.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If the browser cannot find all media tracks with the specified types that meet the constraints given, then the returned promise is rejected with `NotFoundError` `DOMException`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] For both `video` and `audio`, its value is either a boolean or an object.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] A `Promise` whose fulfillment handler receives a `MediaStream` object when the requested media has successfully been obtained.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Although the user and operating system both granted access to the hardware device, and no hardware issues occurred that would cause a `NotReadableError` `DOMException`, throw if some problem occurred which prevented the device from being used.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if current document is not fully active.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if one or more of the requested source devices cannot be used at this time.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] This will happen if the browsing context is insecure (that is, the page was loaded using HTTP rather than HTTPS).
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] It also happens if the user has specified that the current browsing instance is not permitted access to the device, the user has denied access for the current session, or the user has denied all access to user media devices globally.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] On browsers that support managing media permissions with Permissions Policy, this error is returned if Permissions Policy is not configured to allow access to the input source(s).
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if no media tracks of the type specified were found that satisfy the given constraints.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if, although the user granted permission to use the matching devices, a hardware error occurred at the operating system, browser, or Web page level which prevented access to the device.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if the specified constraints resulted in no candidate devices which met the criteria requested.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The error is an object of type `OverconstrainedError`, and has a `constraint` property whose string value is the name of a constraint which was impossible to meet, and a `message` property containing a human-readable string explaining the problem.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if user media support is disabled on the `Document` on which `getUserMedia()` was called.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The mechanism by which user media support is enabled and disabled is left up to the individual user agent.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Thrown if the list of constraints specified is empty, or has all constraints set to `false`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] This can also happen if you try to call `getUserMedia()` in an insecure context, since `navigator.mediaDevices` is `undefined` in an insecure context.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] As an API that may involve significant privacy concerns, `getUserMedia()`'s specification lays out a wide array of privacy and security requirements that browsers are obligated to meet.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] `getUserMedia()` is a powerful feature that can only be used in secure contexts; in insecure contexts, `navigator.mediaDevices` is `undefined`, preventing access to `getUserMedia()`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] A secure context is, in short, a page loaded using HTTPS or the `file:///` URL scheme, or a page loaded from `localhost`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] In addition, user permission is always required to access the user's audio and video inputs.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Only a window's top-level document context for a valid origin can even request permission to use `getUserMedia()`, unless the top-level context expressly grants permission for a given `<iframe>` to do so using Permissions Policy.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Otherwise, the user will never even be asked for permission to use the input devices.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] For additional details on these requirements and rules, how they are reflected in the context in which your code is running, and about how browsers manage user privacy and security issues, read on.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] As an API that may involve significant privacy concerns, `getUserMedia()` is held by the specification to very specific requirements for user notification and permission management.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] First, `getUserMedia()` must always get user permission before opening any media gathering input such as a webcam or microphone.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Browsers may offer a once-per-domain permission feature, but they must ask at least the first time, and the user must specifically grant ongoing permission if they choose to do so.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Of equal importance are the rules around notification.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Browsers are required to display an indicator that shows that a camera or microphone is in use, above and beyond any hardware indicator that may exist.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] They must also show an indicator that permission has been granted to use a device for input, even if the device is not actively recording at the moment.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] For example in Firefox, the URL bar displays a pulsing red icon to indicate that recording is underway.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The icon is gray if the permission is in place but recording is not currently underway.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The device's physical light is used to indicate whether or not recording is currently active.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If you've muted your camera (so-called "facemuting"), your camera's activity light goes out to indicate that the camera is not actively recording you, without discarding the permission to resume using the camera once muting is over.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] There are a number of ways security management and controls in a user agent can cause `getUserMedia()` to return a security-related error.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The two Permissions Policy directives that apply to `getUserMedia()` are `camera` and `microphone`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If you're using `getUserMedia()` within an `<iframe>`, you can request permission just for that frame, which is clearly more secure than requesting a more general permission.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The `getUserMedia()` method is only available in secure contexts.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] A secure context is one the browser is reasonably confident contains a document which was loaded securely, using HTTPS/TLS, and has limited exposure to insecure contexts.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If a document isn't loaded in a secure context, the `navigator.mediaDevices` property is `undefined`, making access to `getUserMedia()` impossible.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Attempting to access `getUserMedia()` in this situation will result in a `TypeError`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Because of the obvious security concern associated with `getUserMedia()` if used unexpectedly or without security being carefully managed, it can only be used in secure contexts.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] There are a number of insecure ways to load a document that might, in turn, attempt to call `getUserMedia()`.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Below are some examples of the `constraints` parameter.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] While information about a user's cameras and microphones are inaccessible for privacy reasons, an application can request the camera and microphone capabilities it needs and wants, using additional constraints.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The browser will try to honor the constraints, and will return a matching track if supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If not supported, the browser may attempt to crop and downscale a higher resolution stream from the underlying hardware in order to match the constraint (and might also reduce the frame rate if that was constrained).
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The browser may return another resolution if an exact match is not available and the source is not to be scaled.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] To *require* a capability and fail if it is not available, use the keywords `min`, `max`, or `exact` (a.k.a.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] If no camera exists with this resolution or higher, then the returned promise will be rejected with `OverconstrainedError`, and the user will not be prompted.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The reason for the difference in behavior is that the keywords `min`, `max`, and `exact` are inherently mandatory — whereas plain values and a keyword called `ideal` are not.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] An `ideal` value, when used, has gravity — which means that the browser will try to find the setting (and camera, if you have more than one), with the smallest fitness distance from the ideal values given.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Another non-number constraint is the `deviceId` constraint.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] The above will return the camera you requested, or a different camera if that specific camera is no longer available.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Browsers' internally-available information, such as user preference, may also override your request.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] For example, when the user was asked for camera permissions, the camera they selected may take priority over the one you requested.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] This example gives a preference for camera resolution, and assigns the resulting `MediaStream` object to a video element.
[src:webrtc/getusermedia] Lower frame-rates may be desirable in some cases, like WebRTC transmissions with bandwidth restrictions.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] The **`RTCDataChannel`** interface represents a network channel which can be used for bidirectional peer-to-peer transfers of arbitrary data.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Every data channel is associated with an `RTCPeerConnection`, and each peer connection can have up to a theoretical maximum of 65,534 data channels (the actual limit may vary from browser to browser).
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] To create a data channel and ask a remote peer to join you, call the `RTCPeerConnection`'s `createDataChannel()` method.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] The peer being invited to exchange data receives a `datachannel` event (which has type `RTCDataChannelEvent`) to let it know the data channel has been added to the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] `RTCDataChannel` is a transferable object.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] A string specifying the type of object that should be used to represent binary data received on the `RTCDataChannel`.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Values are the same as allowed on the `WebSocket.binaryType` property: `blob` if `Blob` objects are being used, or `arraybuffer` if `ArrayBuffer` objects are being used.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns the number of bytes of data currently queued to be sent over the data channel.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Specifies the number of bytes of buffered outgoing data that is considered "low".
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns an ID number (between 0 and 65,534) which uniquely identifies the `RTCDataChannel`.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns a string that contains a name describing the data channel.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] These labels are not required to be unique.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns the amount of time, in milliseconds, the browser is allowed to take to attempt to transmit a message, as set when the data channel was created, or `null`.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns the maximum number of times the browser should try to retransmit a message before giving up, as set when the data channel was created, or `null`, which indicates that there is no maximum.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Indicates whether the `RTCDataChannel`'s connection was negotiated by the Web app (`true`) or by the WebRTC layer (`false`).
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Indicates whether or not the data channel guarantees in-order delivery of messages; the default is `true`, which indicates that the data channel is indeed ordered.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns a string indicating the priority of the data channel, as set when the data channel was created, or as assigned by the user agent.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns a string containing the name of the subprotocol in use.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] If no protocol was specified when the data channel was created, then this property's value is the empty string (`""`).
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Returns a string which indicates the state of the data channel's underlying data connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] It can have one of the following values: `connecting`, `open`, `closing`, or `closed`.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Indicates whether or not the data channel is *reliable*.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Either peer is permitted to call this method to initiate closure of the channel.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sends data across the data channel to the remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sent when the number of bytes of data in the outgoing data buffer falls below the value specified by `bufferedAmountLowThreshold`.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sent when the underlying data transport closes.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sent when the underlying data transport is about to start closing.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sent when an error occurs on the data channel.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sent when a message has been received from the remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] The message contents can be found in the event's `data` property.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Sent when the data channel is first opened, or when an existing data channel's underlying connection re-opens.
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] The underlying data format is defined by the IEEE specification SDP Offer/Answer Procedures for SCTP over DTLS Transport(RFC 8841).
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] The current format specifies its protocol as either `"UDP/DTLS/SCTP"` (UDP carrying DTLS carrying SCTP) or `"TCP/DTLS/SCTP"` (TCP carrying DTLS carrying SCTP).
[src:webrtc/rtcdatachannel] Older browsers may only specify `"DTLS/SCTP"`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] The **`RTCPeerConnection`** interface represents a WebRTC connection between the local computer and a remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] It provides methods to connect to a remote peer, maintain and monitor the connection, and close the connection once it's no longer needed.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a new `RTCPeerConnection`, representing a connection between the local device and a remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a boolean value which indicates whether or not the remote peer can accept trickled ICE candidates.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Indicates the current state of the peer connection by returning one of the strings: `new`, `connecting`, `connected`, `disconnected`, `failed`, or `closed`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSessionDescription` object describing the local end of the connection as it was most recently successfully negotiated since the last time this `RTCPeerConnection` finished negotiating and connecting to a remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Also included is a list of any ICE candidates that may already have been generated by the ICE agent since the offer or answer represented by the description was first instantiated.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSessionDescription` object describing the remote end of the connection as it was most recently successfully negotiated since the last time this `RTCPeerConnection` finished negotiating and connecting to a remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a string which state of the ICE agent associated with this RTCPeerConnection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] It can be one of the following values: `new`, `checking`, `connected`, `completed`, `failed`, `disconnected`, or `closed`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a string that describes connection's ICE gathering state.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This lets you detect, for example, when collection of ICE candidates has finished.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Possible values are: `new`, `gathering`, or `complete`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a string containing the endpoint the application can navigate to, to log users in to the identity provider (IdP).
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSessionDescription` describing the session for the local end of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] If it has not yet been set, returns `null`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to an `RTCIdentityAssertion` which contains a string identifying the remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Once this promise resolves successfully, the resulting identity is the target peer identity and will not change for the duration of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSessionDescription` object describing a pending configuration change for the local end of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This does not describe the connection as it currently stands, but as it may exist in the near future.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSessionDescription` object describing a pending configuration change for the remote end of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSessionDescription` object describing the session, including configuration and media information, for the remote end of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] If this hasn't been set yet, this returns `null`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an `RTCSctpTransport` object describing the SCTP transport layer over which SCTP data is being sent and received.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] If SCTP hasn't been negotiated, this value is `null`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a string describing the state of the signaling process on the local end of the connection while connecting or reconnecting to another peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] It is one of the following values: `stable`, `have-local-offer`, `have-remote-offer`, `have-local-pranswer`, `have-remote-pranswer`, or `closed`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Creates an X.509 certificate and its corresponding private key, returning a `Promise` that resolves with the new `RTCCertificate` once it is generated.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Adds a new remote candidate to the `RTCPeerConnection`'s remote description, which describes the state of the remote end of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Adds a new `MediaStreamTrack` to the set of tracks which will be transmitted to the other peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Creates a new `RTCRtpTransceiver` and adds it to the set of transceivers associated with the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Each transceiver represents a bidirectional stream, with both an `RTCRtpSender` and an `RTCRtpReceiver` associated with it.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Initiates the creation of an SDP answer to an offer received from a remote peer during the offer/answer negotiation of a WebRTC connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] The answer contains information about any media already attached to the session, codecs and options supported by the browser, and any ICE candidates already gathered.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Initiates the creation a new channel linked with the remote peer, over which any kind of data may be transmitted.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This can be useful for back-channel content, such as images, file transfer, text chat, game update packets, and so forth.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Initiates the creation of an SDP offer for the purpose of starting a new WebRTC connection to a remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an object which indicates the current configuration of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Initiates the gathering of an identity assertion and returns a `Promise` which resolves to an identity assertion encoded as a string.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This has an effect only if `signalingState` is not `closed`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an array of `RTCRtpReceiver` objects, each of which represents one RTP receiver.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns an array of `RTCRtpSender` objects, each of which represents the RTP sender responsible for transmitting one track's data.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a `Promise` which resolves with data providing statistics about either the overall connection or about the specified `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Returns a list of all the `RTCRtpTransceiver` objects being used to send and receive data on the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Tells the local end of the connection to stop sending media from the specified track, without actually removing the corresponding `RTCRtpSender` from the list of senders as reported by `getSenders()`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] If the track is already stopped, or is not in the connection's senders list, this method has no effect.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Allows to easily request that ICE candidate gathering be redone on both ends of the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This simplifies the process by allowing the same method to be used by either the caller or the receiver to trigger an ICE restart.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sets the current configuration of the connection based on the values included in the specified object.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This lets you change the ICE servers used by the connection and which transport policies to use.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sets the Identity Provider (IdP) to the triplet given in parameter: its name, the protocol used to communicate with it and a username.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] The protocol and the username are optional.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Changes the local description associated with the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This description specifies the properties of the local end of the connection, including the media format.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] It returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled once the description has been changed, asynchronously.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sets the specified session description as the remote peer's current offer or answer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] The description specifies the properties of the remote end of the connection, including the media format.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Adds a `MediaStream` as a local source of audio or video.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Instead of using this obsolete method, you should instead use `addTrack()` once for each track you wish to send to the remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Creates a new `RTCDTMFSender`, associated to a specific `MediaStreamTrack`, that will be able to send DTMF phone signaling over the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Removes a `MediaStream` as a local source of audio or video.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Because this method is obsolete, you should instead use `removeTrack()`.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when the overall connectivity status of the `RTCPeerConnection` changes.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when the remote peer adds an `RTCDataChannel` to the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent to request that the specified candidate be transmitted to the remote peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent to the connection if an error occurred during ICE candidate gathering.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when the state of the ICE connection changes, such as when it disconnects.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when the ICE layer's gathering state, reflected by `iceGatheringState`, changes.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] This indicates whether ICE negotiation has not yet begun (`new`), has begun gathering candidates (`gathering`), or has completed (`complete`).
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when negotiation or renegotiation of the ICE connection needs to be performed; this can happen both when first opening a connection as well as when it is necessary to adapt to changing network conditions.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] The receiver should respond by creating an offer and sending it to the other peer.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when the connection's ICE signaling state changes.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent after a new track has been added to one of the `RTCRtpReceiver` instances which comprise the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when a new `MediaStream` has been added to the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Instead of listening for this obsolete event, you should listen for `track` events; one is sent for each `MediaStreamTrack` added to the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Sent when a `MediaStream` is removed from the connection.
[src:webrtc/rtcpeerconnection] Instead of listening for this obsolete event, you should listen for `removetrack` events on each stream.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Supported by Apple, Google, Microsoft, Mozilla, and Opera, WebRTC specifications have been published by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) and the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:webrtc/webrtc] ICE, STUN and TURN are the NAT traversal techniques used to connect to remote peers.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In May 2010, Google bought Global IP Solutions or GIPS, a VoIP and videoconferencing software company that had developed many components required for RTC, such as codecs and echo cancellation techniques.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Google open-sourced the GIPS technology and engaged with relevant standards bodies at the IETF and W3C to ensure industry consensus.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In May 2011, Google released an open-source project for browser-based real-time communication known as WebRTC.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] This has been followed by ongoing work to standardize the relevant protocols in the IETF and browser APIs in the W3C.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In January 2011, Ericsson Labs built the first implementation of WebRTC using a modified WebKit library.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In October 2011, the W3C published its first draft for the spec.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] WebRTC milestones include the first cross-browser video call (February 2013), first cross-browser data transfers (February 2014), and as of July 2014 Google Hangouts was "kind of" using WebRTC.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] The W3C draft API was based on preliminary work done in the WHATWG.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] It was referred to as the ConnectionPeer API, and a pre-standards concept implementation was created at Ericsson Labs.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In November 2017, the WebRTC 1.0 specification transitioned from Working Draft to Candidate Recommendation.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In January 2021, the WebRTC 1.0 specification transitioned from Candidate Recommendation to Recommendation.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] The WebRTC API includes **no provisions for signaling**, that is discovering peers to connect to and determine how to establish connections among them.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Applications use Interactive Connectivity Establishment for connections and are responsible for managing sessions, possibly relying on any of Session Initiation Protocol, Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP), Message Queuing Telemetry Transport, Matrix, or another protocol.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Signaling may depend on one or more servers.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] RFC 7478 requires implementations to provide PCMA/PCMU (RFC 3551), Telephone Event as DTMF (RFC 4733), and Opus (RFC 6716) audio codecs as minimum capabilities.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] The PeerConnection, data channel and media capture browser APIs are detailed in the W3C specification.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] W3C is developing ORTC (Object Real-Time Communications) for WebRTC.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] WebRTC allows browsers to stream files directly to one another, reducing or entirely removing the need for server-side file hosting.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] WebTorrent uses a WebRTC transport to enable peer-to-peer file sharing using the BitTorrent protocol in the browser.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Some file-sharing websites use it to allow users to send files directly to one another in their browsers, although this requires the uploader to keep the tab open until the file has been downloaded.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] A few CDNs, such as the Microsoft-owned Peer5, use the client's bandwidth to upload media to other connected peers, enabling each peer to act as an edge server.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Although initially developed for web browsers, WebRTC has applications for non-browser devices, including mobile platforms and IoT devices.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Examples include browser-based VoIP telephony, also called cloud phones or web phones, which allow calls to be made and received from within a web browser, replacing the requirement to download and install a softphone.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] WebRTC establishes a standard set of codecs which all compliant browsers are required to implement (underlined).
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Some browsers may also support other codecs.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] In January 2015, TorrentFreak reported a serious security flaw in browsers supporting WebRTC, that compromised the security of VPN tunnels by exposing a user's true IP address.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] The IP address read requests are not visible in the browser's developer console, and they are not blocked by most ad blocking, privacy and security add-ons, enabling online tracking despite precautions.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] It has been reported that the cause of the address leak is not a bug that can be patched, but is foundational to the way WebRTC operates; however, there are several solutions to mitigate the problem.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] WebRTC leakage can be tested for, and solutions are offered for most browsers.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] WebRTC can be disabled, if not required, in most browsers.
[src:webrtc/webrtc] The uBlock Origin add-on can fix this problem (as some browsers now fix this problem by themselves, from uBlock Origin v1.38 onwards this option has been disabled on these browsers).
[src:webrtc/webrtc] Like HTTP3/QUIC, WebRTC cannot be tunneled over TOR because TOR doesn't support UDP, thus most WebRTC applications don't work without bypassing TOR or using TURN servers.
